    <subsection xml:id="subsec-units-of-measuring-temperatures">
      <title>Units of measuring temperatures.</title>
      <activity>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Hezron Samson, A grade 7 student visited a health facility centre and came across the equipment shown below.
          </p>
          <image width="=59%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              % Thermometer body
              \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (12,0.5);
              % Scale marks and labels (Celsius)
              \foreach \x in {0,1,...,11} {
              \draw[thick=blue] (\x,0.5) -- (\x,0.7);
              \node[above] at (\x,0.7) {\small \pgfmathparse{55-\x*5}\pgfmathresult};  }
              \node[above right] at (12,0.7) {°C};
              % Scale marks and labels (Kelvin)
              \foreach \x in {0,1,...,11} {
              \draw[thick=blue] (\x,0) -- (\x,-0.2);
              \node[below] at (\x,-0.2) {\small \pgfmathparse{328-\x*5}\pgfmathresult}; }
              \node[below right] at (12,-0.2) {K};
              % Temperature indicator (Adjustable)
              \fill[purple] (8,0) rectangle (12,0.5); % Adjust "8" to change the filled region
              \draw[thick] (12,0.25) circle (0.4); % Bulb at the end
              \fill[purple] (12,0.25) circle (0.4);   % Fill the bulb
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the <m>\textbf{name}</m>  of the equipment? 
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  State <m>\textbf{two functions}</m>  of the equipment.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  List <m>\textbf{five areas}</m> where it can be used.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Identify the symbol<m>{\color{blue}(°C)} </m>in the instrument above. What does the symbol <m>{\color{blue}(°C)} </m> stand for?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Identify the symbol<m>{\color{blue}(K)} </m> in the instrument. What does the symbol <m>{\color{blue}(K)} </m> represent?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </activity>
      <explanation>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Temperature is measured using a <m>{\color{blue}\text {thermometer}}.</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The most common scales used are the <m>{\color{blue}\text {Celcious scale}(^\circ C )}.</m> and the <m>{\color{blue}\text {Kelvin (K) scale}}.</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The boiling point of water at sea level is <m>{\color{blue}\text {100} ^\circ C}</m>  or <m>{\color{blue}\text {373 Kelvin}}.</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The freezing point of water at sea level is <m>{\color{blue}\text {0} ^\circ C}</m>  or <m>{\color{blue}\text {273 Kelvin}}.</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The normal temperature of a human body is about <m>{\color{blue}\text {37} ^\circ C}</m>  or <m>{\color{blue}\text {310 Kelvin}}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </explanation>
